<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- PART 1 — TECHNICAL                                          -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

<h1 class="nobreak">PART 1 &mdash; Technical Architecture Changes</h1>

<h2>1.1 &nbsp; Overview</h2>
<p>This session transformed the IFQM Ideation Tool from a single-organisation monolithic application into a multi-tenant SaaS platform. Three major workstreams were completed in this session:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Multi-tenant database architecture</strong> &mdash; each MSME organisation receives an isolated MySQL database, provisioned automatically at sign-up.</li>
  <li><strong>Expanded role hierarchy</strong> &mdash; from 5 to 8 levels, with correct RBAC propagation across all API endpoints and the frontend.</li>
  <li><strong>Session security hardening</strong> &mdash; idle-timeout enforcement on both the server (PHP) and the client (JavaScript).</li>
</ul>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>1.2 &nbsp; Previous Architecture</h2>

<h3>Database Layer</h3>
<p>A single MySQL database named <strong>ifqm_ideation</strong> held all users, ideas, workflows, votes, and attachments. There was no tenant isolation — all data coexisted in shared tables. A second organisation signing up would have shared the exact same rows.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Previous State</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Database count</td><td>1 (ifqm_ideation)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Tenant registry</td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Data isolation</td><td>None — all organisations in shared tables</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Org provisioning</td><td>Manual developer work (hours to days)</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Authentication</h3>
<p>Login accepted only <code>email</code> + <code>password</code>. PHP looked up the user directly in <code>ifqm_ideation.users</code>. The session cookie lifetime was set to 28,800 seconds (8 hours) via <code>session_set_cookie_params()</code> in <code>api/auth.php</code>, but this call was made only on the login request. No <code>last_activity</code> tracking existed — a session could outlive the intended window. No client-side expiry guard existed at all.</p>

<h3>Role System &mdash; 5 Roles</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Role</th><th>Permissions</th></tr>
  <tr><td>employee</td><td>Submit ideas; view own ideas</td></tr>
  <tr><td>manager</td><td>Review direct reports&rsquo; ideas; analytics; audit trail</td></tr>
  <tr><td>executive</td><td>Review all ideas; mark as Implemented</td></tr>
  <tr><td>admin</td><td>Full org access; user list (read-only in old panel)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>super_admin</td><td>Legacy root role; same effective permissions as admin</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Idea Review Flow (Previous)</h3>
<p>Employee submits &rarr; routed to direct manager via <code>manager_id</code> &rarr; manager Approves / Rejects / marks Under Review &rarr; executive or admin marks as Implemented. <strong>Single-hop, no automatic escalation between levels.</strong></p>

<h3>Known Bugs at Start of Session</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Bug 1 &mdash; Admin panel always visible:</strong> <code>initApp()</code> called <code>loadDashboard()</code> and <code>loadMyIdeas()</code> for regular users but never called <code>navigate('dashboard')</code>. Whatever page was active in the previous browser session &mdash; for example the admin panel from a prior admin login &mdash; remained visible after a new employee logged in.</li>
  <li><strong>Bug 2 &mdash; Session never expired:</strong> No <code>visibilitychange</code> listener, no periodic polling, no client-side expiry check. A browser tab left open indefinitely stayed authenticated.</li>
  <li><strong>Bug 3 &mdash; Role dropdown limited to 2 options:</strong> Both the backend allowed-roles array and the frontend dropdown were hardcoded to show only <code>employee</code> and <code>manager</code>, even though <code>executive</code> and <code>admin</code> existed in the schema.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>1.3 &nbsp; New Architecture</h2>

<h3>Multi-Tenant Database Pattern</h3>
<p>The system now uses the <strong>master-tenant registry pattern</strong>:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Component</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>ifqm_master</code></td><td>Registry database. Contains <code>tenants</code> table (org metadata + DB credentials) and <code>platform_admins</code> table (IFQM vendor staff). Never exposed to org users.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>ifqm_{slug}</code></td><td>One isolated MySQL database per organisation, created dynamically at org creation time (e.g., <code>ifqm_jain</code>, <code>ifqm_acme</code>).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>schema.sql</code></td><td>Template applied to each new tenant database. Contains all table definitions, the expanded role ENUM, and new columns.</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Tenant Resolution &mdash; resolveTenant()</h3>
<p>Every incoming API request calls <code>resolveTenant()</code> which selects the correct database connection via a 5-step priority chain:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Session org_slug</strong> &mdash; set at login, persists for the session lifetime.</li>
  <li><strong>?org= URL parameter</strong> &mdash; used on initial page load or in the login POST body.</li>
  <li><strong>Domain-based match</strong> &mdash; <code>tenants.domain</code> column checked against the <code>HTTP_HOST</code> header.</li>
  <li><strong>Default tenant flag</strong> &mdash; <code>tenants.is_default = 1</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Hardcoded fallback</strong> &mdash; <code>ifqm_ideation</code>, which keeps existing single-tenant installs working.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Authentication Flow (New)</h3>
<p>The login request now includes three fields: <code>email</code>, <code>password</code>, and <code>org_slug</code>. The server processes them through two paths:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Path A &mdash; Platform Admin:</strong> Checked first against <code>ifqm_master.platform_admins</code>. If matched, session stores <code>platform_admin = true</code> but no <code>org_slug</code>. Can access only <code>api/platform.php</code> endpoints.</li>
  <li><strong>Path B &mdash; Tenant User:</strong> <code>org_slug</code> injected into GET params so <code>resolveTenant()</code> connects to the correct DB. Queries that tenant&rsquo;s <code>users</code> table. On success, session stores <code>user_id</code>, <code>user</code> (full object), <code>org_slug</code>, and <code>last_activity = time()</code>.</li>
</ul>

<h3>New API Endpoints</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Method</th><th>Endpoint</th><th>Description</th></tr>
  <tr><td>GET</td><td>platform.php?action=tenants</td><td>List all orgs with aggregate stats (no idea content)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>GET</td><td>platform.php?action=tenant_detail&amp;id=X</td><td>Full read-only view of one org (platform admin only)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>GET</td><td>platform.php?action=tenant_hierarchy&amp;id=X</td><td>User org tree (privacy-safe: no idea titles or content)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>POST</td><td>platform.php?action=create_tenant</td><td>Creates org DB, runs schema, inserts tenant record, creates org admin</td></tr>
  <tr><td>POST</td><td>users.php?action=create_user</td><td>Creates a user within the current org</td></tr>
  <tr><td>POST</td><td>users.php?action=update_user</td><td>Updates user fields and/or role</td></tr>
  <tr><td>POST</td><td>users.php?action=delete_user</td><td>Deletes (or deactivates if the user has submitted ideas)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>GET</td><td>users.php?action=managers</td><td>Dropdown list: all supervisor-level users in current org</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Expanded Role Hierarchy &mdash; 8 Levels</h3>
<p>The <code>role</code> ENUM was expanded from 5 to 9 values (<code>super_admin</code> retained for legacy):</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Role</th><th>Level</th><th>Review Queue</th><th>Analytics / Audit</th><th>Admin Panel</th></tr>
  <tr><td>trainee</td><td>1</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>employee</td><td>2</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>team_lead</td><td>3</td><td>Direct reports only</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>project_lead</td><td>4</td><td>Direct reports only</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>manager</td><td>5</td><td>Direct reports only</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>senior_manager</td><td>6</td><td>Direct reports only</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>executive</td><td>7</td><td>ALL ideas org-wide</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
  <tr><td>admin</td><td>8</td><td>ALL ideas org-wide</td><td>&#10003;</td><td>&#10003;</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>RBAC Changes Across the Codebase</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>ideas.php review action:</strong> was <code>requireRole('manager','admin','executive','super_admin')</code>. Now includes <code>team_lead</code>, <code>project_lead</code>, <code>senior_manager</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>ideas.php list action:</strong> role-scoped idea visibility now uses <code>in_array()</code> checks against named role groups: <code>individualRoles</code> (trainee, employee) and <code>teamRoles</code> (team_lead through senior_manager).</li>
  <li><strong>users.php analytics + audit:</strong> <code>senior_manager</code> added to allowed roles.</li>
  <li><strong>users.php leaderboard:</strong> was <code>WHERE role='employee'</code>. Changed to <code>WHERE role NOT IN ('admin','super_admin')</code> so all submitters appear.</li>
  <li><strong>users.php managers dropdown:</strong> now includes <code>team_lead</code>, <code>project_lead</code>, <code>senior_manager</code> as valid parent nodes.</li>
  <li><strong>users.php create/update:</strong> admin can create trainee through executive (7 roles); only super_admin can also create admin.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Session Security &mdash; Three Enforcement Layers</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>PHP requireAuth():</strong> Every API call checks <code>(time() - last_activity) &gt; SESSION_LIFETIME</code>. If exceeded: <code>session_destroy()</code>, HTTP 401 with <code>expired: true</code> flag.</li>
  <li><strong>index.php page load:</strong> Same idle check runs on every page refresh before PHP renders the app. Expired sessions are destroyed before <code>currentUser</code> is ever set.</li>
  <li><strong>JavaScript:</strong> <code>document.addEventListener('visibilitychange')</code> fires <code>checkSession()</code> when the browser tab becomes active after being hidden. <code>setInterval(checkSession, 600000)</code> polls <code>api/auth.php?action=me</code> every 10 minutes. Both redirect to the login screen on an unauthenticated response.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Bug Fixes Delivered</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Navigate fix:</strong> <code>initApp()</code> now resets all active page and nav states at the top, then explicitly calls <code>navigate('dashboard')</code> for regular users. Stale page state from a previous session cannot persist.</li>
  <li><strong>Role dropdown fix:</strong> New <code>buildRoleOptions()</code> JavaScript function generates dropdown HTML dynamically based on <code>currentUser.role</code>, replacing hardcoded two-option strings.</li>
  <li><strong>formatRole() and ROLE_COLORS:</strong> All 8 roles now have display names and distinct colour codes for consistent UI representation across the entire application.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>1.4 &nbsp; Files Changed</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>File</th><th>Change</th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>api/config.php</code></td><td><code>resolveTenant()</code> rewritten for slug-based routing; <code>requireAuth()</code> updated with idle-timeout enforcement; <code>masterDb()</code>, <code>uploadDir()</code>, <code>uploadUrl()</code> helpers added</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>api/auth.php</code></td><td><code>org_slug</code> field added to login; platform_admin authentication path; <code>last_activity</code> set on login; <code>org_slug</code> cleared from session on platform login</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>api/platform.php</code></td><td>All 4 tenant management endpoints; <code>safeTenant()</code> helper strips DB credentials before sending to client</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>api/users.php</code></td><td>create/update/delete user endpoints; managers dropdown; expanded role allowlists; leaderboard role filter fix; hierarchy ORDER BY updated</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>api/ideas.php</code></td><td>3 &times; <code>requireRole()</code> calls updated; list action uses role-group arrays; review query split on teamRoles vs executive/admin</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>index.php</code></td><td>Multi-tenant login UI with org_slug field; <code>initApp()</code> navigate fix + page reset; session guard JS; <code>buildRoleOptions()</code>; <code>formatRole()</code> and <code>ROLE_COLORS</code> for new roles; <code>visibilitychange</code> + <code>setInterval</code> session checks</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>schema.sql</code></td><td>Role ENUM expanded to 9 values; <code>status ENUM('active','inactive')</code> on users; <code>upvotes</code>/<code>downvotes</code> on ideas; <code>idea_community_votes</code> table added</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>master.sql</code></td><td><strong>New file.</strong> Creates <code>ifqm_master</code> database; <code>tenants</code> table; <code>platform_admins</code> table; seeds <code>platform@ifqm.io</code></td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>cleanup.sql</code></td><td><strong>New file.</strong> Wipes <code>ifqm_ideation</code> sample data; <code>ALTER TABLE</code> migrations for the existing install</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>1.5 &nbsp; Data Isolation Guarantee</h2>
<p>Tenant data separation is enforced at the <strong>database connection level</strong>, not merely at the application logic level. The <code>db()</code> function in <code>config.php</code> opens a PDO connection to the resolved tenant&rsquo;s own MySQL database. An API call authenticated to Org A&rsquo;s session physically connects to Org A&rsquo;s database. Even if a SQL injection vulnerability existed somewhere in the application code, it could only operate within that one tenant&rsquo;s database schema. There are no shared tables, no shared schemas, and no cross-tenant foreign keys anywhere in the system.</p>


<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- PART 2 — LAYMAN                                             -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

<h1>PART 2 &mdash; Plain-Language Explanation</h1>

<h2>2.1 &nbsp; What is the IFQM Ideation Tool?</h2>
<p>The IFQM Ideation Tool is a <strong>digital suggestion box &mdash; but a very smart one</strong>. It allows every employee in a manufacturing company to submit ideas for improvements: how to reduce waste, speed up a process, save costs, improve safety, or better serve customers.</p>
<p>Those ideas then go through a structured review by team leaders, managers, and directors. The best ones get implemented. And the employees who suggested them earn points and recognition &mdash; instead of their ideas disappearing into a dusty physical box that nobody opens.</p>
<p>Think of it as replacing the suggestion box in the factory canteen with a modern system that tracks every idea, uses AI to score its quality, routes it to the right reviewer, and tells the employee exactly what happened to their suggestion &mdash; and why.</p>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>2.2 &nbsp; What Changed in This Session &mdash; The Simple Version</h2>

<h3>The Problem We Were Solving</h3>
<p>IFQM recently had meetings with several MSMEs &mdash; small and medium manufacturing companies &mdash; who were interested in using this tool for their employees. The problem: the tool was originally built for just one company. If Jain Industries and Mahindra Components both started using the same system, could Jain&rsquo;s employees accidentally see Mahindra&rsquo;s confidential ideas? With the old system, the honest answer was: <em>potentially yes</em>. That was unacceptable.</p>

<h3>The Old System &mdash; One Shared Room for Everyone</h3>
<p>Imagine 10 different companies sharing one large office with no walls, no private desks, and everyone&rsquo;s files stacked on the same table. Anyone could walk up and read anyone else&rsquo;s documents at any time. That was the old IFQM system &mdash; one large shared database with no separation between organisations.</p>
<p>There was also only one entrance with one security desk. You walked in, said your name and password, and you were inside &mdash; with no need to say which company you were from.</p>

<h3>The New System &mdash; A Secure Apartment Building</h3>
<p>Now picture a well-managed apartment building:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The <strong>building manager</strong> (IFQM) sits at the front desk and holds the master list of all apartments</li>
  <li>Each company gets <strong>their own private flat</strong> (their own isolated database) &mdash; completely locked</li>
  <li>When a new company signs up, IFQM creates a brand new empty flat and hands the keys to that company&rsquo;s admin</li>
  <li>The building manager can see how many people live in each flat, and whether the lights are on &mdash; but <strong>cannot read the private papers inside</strong></li>
  <li>Flats are completely separated &mdash; Jain Industries&rsquo; flat cannot be accessed from Mahindra&rsquo;s flat, under any circumstances</li>
</ul>

<h3>How a New Company Gets Onboarded &mdash; Step by Step</h3>
<p>Before this change, setting up a new company required a developer to manually create databases and configure servers &mdash; taking hours. Now the process is:</p>
<ol>
  <li>IFQM Platform Admin logs into the IFQM management dashboard</li>
  <li>Clicks &ldquo;New Organisation&rdquo;, enters the company name, and sets up the first admin account and password</li>
  <li>The system automatically creates a private database for that company in about 2 seconds</li>
  <li>The company admin receives their unique login link (e.g., <em>ifqm.io/?org=jain-industries</em>)</li>
  <li>The company admin logs in and starts adding their team members</li>
  <li>Employees start submitting ideas &mdash; all within their own private, isolated space</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Total time: approximately 2 minutes. No developer involvement required after setup.</strong></p>

<h3>The New Employee Levels &mdash; Matching Real Company Structure</h3>
<p>The old system had only 5 types of users. But a real MSME has many more levels &mdash; Jain Industries might have Trainees on the shop floor, Operators, Team Leaders, Project Leads, Department Managers, Senior Managers, Directors, and an Admin. The old system could not represent this structure. The new system has <strong>8 levels</strong>, and ideas flow upward through them naturally:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Level</th><th>Role</th><th>What They Do in the Tool</th></tr>
  <tr><td>1</td><td>Trainee</td><td>New joiners and apprentices. Can submit ideas from day one &mdash; even the newest voice matters.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>2</td><td>Employee</td><td>Regular operators and office staff. The core idea submitters of the organisation.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>3</td><td>Team Lead</td><td>Leads a team of 5&ndash;10 people. The first reviewer of their team members&rsquo; ideas.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>4</td><td>Project Lead</td><td>Manages a specific project. Reviews ideas from their project team.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>5</td><td>Manager</td><td>Department head. Reviews all ideas from everyone who reports to them. Also gets analytics reports.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>6</td><td>Senior Manager</td><td>Oversees multiple departments or a business unit. Same review powers as a manager but wider visibility.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>7</td><td>Executive</td><td>Director, VP, or CXO level. Sees all ideas across the whole company. Makes the final decision to implement.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>8</td><td>Org Admin</td><td>The HR or IT person who manages the system. Can add, edit, and deactivate employee accounts.</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Security Improvement &mdash; Sessions Now Expire Automatically</h3>
<p><strong>Before:</strong> If an employee logged into the IFQM tool on a shared computer in the factory and walked away, anyone who sat down at that computer later could see everything &mdash; the account, the company&rsquo;s ideas, the entire tool.</p>
<p><strong>After:</strong> The system now automatically logs users out after 8 hours of inactivity. If you leave the browser tab open overnight and come back the next morning, you will see the message: <em>&ldquo;Your session has expired &mdash; please sign in again.&rdquo;</em> This protects company data even on shared computers on the production floor.</p>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>2.3 &nbsp; 17 Ideas for Making This Tool Even Better</h2>
<p>After completing these major changes, the development team identified 17 features that would significantly improve the tool for MSME companies. These are grouped by theme and explained in plain language.</p>

<h3>Group A &mdash; Making the Review Process Smoother</h3>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 1 &mdash; Step-by-Step Approval Chain</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Right now, when a Team Lead approves an idea, it simply sits as &ldquo;Approved&rdquo; with no further movement. In the proposed system, approval would automatically move the idea to the next level: Team Lead approves &rarr; goes to Manager &rarr; Manager approves &rarr; goes to Executive &rarr; Executive gives the final green light. Like how a purchase order needs sign-offs from multiple people before it gets processed. Ideas would never get stuck or forgotten at one level.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 2 &mdash; Review Deadlines with Automatic Escalation</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>If a manager has an idea waiting in their review queue and has not acted on it for 7 days, the system sends them a reminder notification and email. After 14 days of no action, the idea automatically escalates to their supervisor. This prevents good ideas from dying in someone&rsquo;s inbox because they were on leave or simply too busy to check the tool.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 3 &mdash; Implementation Tracking Board</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>After an idea is approved, who is actually responsible for doing the work? By when? What is the current progress? Currently the tool has no way to track any of this. This feature would let the Executive assign an implementation owner, set a deadline, and track stages: Not Started &rarr; In Progress &rarr; Completed. After the work is done, the team logs actual results &mdash; time saved, money saved, defects reduced.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 4 &mdash; Email Notifications</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>Currently the tool only shows notifications when a user is already logged in and actively looking at the screen. Most employees will miss these entirely. With email notifications, when your idea gets approved or rejected you receive an email immediately in your inbox. When a manager has unreviewed ideas for more than 3 days, they receive a daily reminder email. Simple and immediately impactful for user engagement.</p>
</div>

<h3>Group B &mdash; Improving the Quality of Ideas</h3>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 5 &mdash; Discussion Threads on Ideas</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Currently a reviewer can only approve or reject an idea. They cannot ask a question or suggest an improvement before making a final decision. With discussion threads, the reviewer could write: &ldquo;I like this idea but can you clarify the estimated cost?&rdquo; and the employee could respond. This back-and-forth dialogue produces much better, more complete ideas before a decision is made, and reduces the number of ideas rejected purely due to missing information.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 6 &mdash; Innovation Challenges and Campaigns</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Instead of employees always guessing what kind of improvements are most needed, management can post a focused challenge with a deadline &mdash; for example: <em>&ldquo;How do we reduce water usage in the plant by 20% before December?&rdquo;</em> Employees then submit ideas specifically for that challenge. This is like an internal hackathon that produces highly targeted, actionable ideas instead of a general mix of suggestions.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 7 &mdash; Smart Duplicate Detection</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Before an employee submits an idea, the system checks whether a very similar idea was already submitted previously. If similar ideas exist, it shows: <em>&ldquo;3 similar ideas have already been suggested &mdash; would you like to collaborate on one of them instead?&rdquo;</em> This reduces duplicated work and encourages team members to build on each other&rsquo;s ideas rather than starting from scratch.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 8 &mdash; Idea Templates</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>Different kinds of improvements need different information. A cost-saving idea needs budget estimates. A safety improvement needs risk details. A process improvement needs before-and-after steps. Templates guide the employee to provide exactly the right information for each type of idea. This makes the reviewer&rsquo;s job significantly faster and ensures ideas are consistently formatted and comparable.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 9 &mdash; Anonymous Submissions</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>In companies with strict hierarchies, some employees are hesitant to put their name on an idea that challenges how their manager currently does things. An optional anonymous mode lets employees submit ideas where their name is hidden from reviewers (but remains visible to the Org Admin for audit purposes). Research consistently shows that offering anonymity significantly increases the volume and boldness of ideas submitted &mdash; especially in manufacturing environments.</p>
</div>

<h3>Group C &mdash; Better Measurement and Reports</h3>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 10 &mdash; ROI Tracking &mdash; Measuring Real Value</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>After an idea is implemented, how much did it actually save? How much time was freed up? Currently there is no way to record or display this. ROI Tracking lets the implementation team log actual results after the work is done &mdash; for example <em>&ldquo;Saved Rs 2.4 lakh in Q1&rdquo;</em> or <em>&ldquo;Reduced defect rate by 8%&rdquo;</em>. Over time, the IFQM platform dashboard shows the total measurable business value the tool has delivered. This is the single most powerful number for convincing an MSME management team to continue using the platform and to expand it to more employees.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 11 &mdash; Export to Excel and PDF</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>Managers frequently need to present idea reports at board meetings or monthly review sessions. Currently, data cannot be exported from the tool &mdash; it can only be viewed on screen. This one-click feature would export idea lists (with filters applied), analytics summaries, leaderboard standings, and audit trails into Excel spreadsheets or PDF files that are immediately ready for a presentation.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 12 &mdash; Dedicated Manager Dashboard</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Managers currently see the same interface layout as regular employees. A manager-specific summary view would show at a glance: how many ideas are waiting for their action right now; how long each idea has been waiting; how their team&rsquo;s idea submission rate compares to other departments in the company; and which team members have not submitted any ideas this month. This helps managers identify and address blockages in the innovation pipeline.</p>
</div>

<h3>Group D &mdash; Customisation and Platform Improvements</h3>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 13 &mdash; Per-Organisation Settings Panel</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Every MSME operates differently. One company might want the review deadline to be 5 days, another wants 15 days. One company might want points for implemented ideas to be worth three times more. Another might want to disable anonymous submissions entirely. A settings panel for each organisation lets them customise the tool to their own work culture and processes &mdash; without IFQM needing to change any code for each client.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 14 &mdash; Bulk Review Actions</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>If a manager has been on leave for a week and returns to find 25 ideas waiting in their review queue, going through them one by one is time-consuming and discouraging. Bulk actions would let them select 10 ideas at once and approve them all with a single shared comment, or mark them all as needing more information. This significantly reduces the friction of managing large idea queues during busy periods.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 15 &mdash; Company-Wide Idea Voting Board</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>Currently employees can only see their own ideas or ideas from their immediate team. An optional company-wide board would let all employees see ideas submitted by colleagues from every department and vote on the ones they believe are most impactful. This creates a sense of company-wide community around innovation, helps surface the most popular ideas faster, and gives executives a democratic signal about which ideas have broad employee support before those ideas even enter the formal review process.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 16 &mdash; Integration with Other Business Systems</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag orange">Medium Impact</span><span class="tag orange">Medium Effort</span></div>
  <p>When an idea gets approved, the system could automatically post a celebratory announcement in the company&rsquo;s WhatsApp group or Microsoft Teams channel. When an idea is marked for implementation, the system could automatically create a task in whatever project management tool the company already uses (like Jira, Trello, or Asana). These automatic connections eliminate manual announcement steps and ensure all systems stay synchronised without extra effort from the team.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea-box">
  <div class="idea-title">Idea 17 &mdash; Mobile App Experience (Install on Phone)</div>
  <div class="idea-tag"><span class="tag">High Impact</span><span class="tag green">Low Effort</span></div>
  <p>The tool already functions on mobile browsers, but employees would use it far more often if they could install it on their phone like a regular app &mdash; with a proper icon on the home screen, offline capability, and push notifications. This is achievable without building an entirely separate mobile application. A technical approach called <em>Progressive Web App (PWA)</em> transforms the existing website into an installable, native-feeling mobile app. This is particularly important for shop floor workers who may not have access to a desk computer during their work day.</p>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────────────── -->
<h2>2.4 &nbsp; Recommended Priority Order for Next Steps</h2>
<p>Based on expected business impact and estimated development effort, the recommended build order is:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Priority</th><th>Feature</th><th>Why It Comes First</th></tr>
  <tr><td>1</td><td>Email Notifications (Idea 4)</td><td>High visibility to all users; moderate effort; immediate daily engagement improvement</td></tr>
  <tr><td>2</td><td>Step-by-Step Approval Chain (Idea 1)</td><td>The most requested feature type in enterprise idea management; addresses the current flat single-hop workflow</td></tr>
  <tr><td>3</td><td>ROI Tracking (Idea 10)</td><td>Directly proves business value at renewal time &mdash; critical for MSME client retention</td></tr>
  <tr><td>4</td><td>Export to Excel / PDF (Idea 11)</td><td>Very commonly needed for board presentations; relatively low development effort</td></tr>
  <tr><td>5</td><td>Review Deadlines and Escalation (Idea 2)</td><td>Prevents idea queue abandonment, which is the most common failure mode for idea management programs</td></tr>
</table>

<br/>
